{"questionId":"2966816","questionHtml":"<p>Use this result to prove that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msup></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>S</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>≤</mo><mfrac><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M1</strong></em> for use of the inequality, which may be seen as an equality.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><mo>≤</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mi>n</mi></msup></math> (as both sides are positive)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>LHS and RHS are equal when all values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math> are equal (to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub>